metadata.name: caravans #32
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by Paul Klee's 'Zwei Kamele und ein Esel' (Two camels and a donkey), abacuses and excessive shopping sprees.

An anonymous caravan makes its way through abstract deserts, carrying their semi-brutalist cargo towards an unknown destination.

All primary proceeds go to the Processing foundation.

Happy birthday fxhash!

Written in JavaScript, rendering to Canvas.

metadata.name: thébaïde #17
metadata.description:
“Thébaïde” is a french word for wild place, remote and peaceful, where to live in a calm retreat. It's also simply a desert and a synonym of solitude. It comes from Thebaid, an arid region of ancient Egypt and Thebes was the capital.

“thébaïde” is my debut on fx(hash), almost one year since my first works minted on Objkt (a series of Indian ink drawings, in January 2022). After learning the basics of creative coding recently, and a few works with this technique, I decided to create a first generative project. With "thébaïde" I chose to express the minimalist and narrative aspects of my artistic approach (though the title and concept emerged at the end). Gradually the work was resonating with philosophical matters I'm obsessed with since years: time, emptiness, human condition, erosion, desire, chance, combining them into a visual metaphor. The view of a vast area, a changing silhouette, an impenetrable monolith or an opening to elsewhere or nothing, day and night and day and night and dawn and dusk — few elements able to compose a meditative and lasting tableau of questions and feelings.

Press “s” in live mode to save the work.
Made with p5js | 2023
Png | 2000 px x 2000 px | 72 ppi

www.antoniowerli.com

metadata.name: Moon Sun Ocean #110
metadata.description:
The secret to happiness is to simplify as much as possible. The details surrounding us must be said goodbye as soon as possible. The best thing we can do is to get started early and get rid of additional complexities as soon as possible. After that, we'll be able to breathe... After that, life will begin again!
There will be many words in this interpretation, despite its simplicity.
Made by p5.js
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Liminal Slippage #68
metadata.description:
Is this a metaphor of thoughts and perceptions slipping in and out the threshold of the mind? Or colours and shapes bleeding into a virtual focus, gaining grain in the process?

At least we know it's two passes through two different GLSL shaders, where simplex noise is computed and reinterpreted in multiple ways.

Press [spacebar] to toggle play/pause.

When paused, press [p] to create hi-res PNG.

metadata.name: Holy Mountain #61
metadata.description:
Mountains throughout human history have taken on deep meanings. Coated with immense sacredness by all peoples in the most different places. Being them as a representation of God himself or being the object of worship. For many the mountains were the very abode of the Gods. They are in the collective unconscious as the ability to connect men and gods, through the flow of energy between earth and heaven.

The symbology is very strong. It unconsciously reminds us of the process of encounter between the loneliness of the earth and the hope of the sky, between the fog that blinds and the cloud that supports, between the abyss of the ground and the proximity of the stars. All this is very charming and fascinating.

All human beings have their own mountain, which demands from each one their limits to reach the top, the desire for the breathtaking view, the fear of falling, but also the hope of the last step at the highest point.

In generative art it couldn't be different, going through all the learning, from its fundamentals, to all the countless hours of tests, to countless moments of problem solving and research and more research. This whole process is without a doubt like climbing a mountain. Thinking about the project is exactly like looking at a mountain and imagining how exhausting it will be all the way to conquer it. Finishing your work is like breathing a sigh of relief, looking down and seeing how hard it was to get there, but at the same time looking ahead and realizing how rewarding it was to be able to have that vision and breathe the refreshing breeze of the moment.

After going through a transformation in my first work, where I transmuted my artistic essence from illustration to generative art. Now I come to this second work that I delved into, and after months of climbing this mountain of mine, I give it to you.


- Press "S" in live view mode after loading to save at 1600x1600px.

metadata.name: Chaos Culture #635
metadata.description:
"Chaos Culture" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

《西遊記》第一回:「混沌未分天地亂，茫茫渺渺無人見。」

Chaos Culture is the final chapter of this series. There is a legend in the East that before Pan Gu opened up the sky and created the earth, the world was a chaotic place, and no one knew its appearance. And I have always been fascinated by this mythical story since he was a child.

These three works have a father-son relationship, Research > Memory > Culture, with each work re-growing through the remnants of the previous work, depending on its image. From the beginning of the creative coding, I like the concept of recursion the most. Here I experiment with my central thinking through this iterative relationship so that the work is not only the shadow of the artist but also the pulling force of repetition.

"混沌" Chaos in Eastern culture represents the initial state of things. This state is consistent with what we believe in generative art: Anything can happen if different forces are applied. Letting chaos grow out of order and then destroying it, the iterative process, is like my usual dialogue with myself, and maybe it's all just a diary.

Through these three series of works, whether I can eventually find everything in my childhood fantasy, I am not sure yet. The only thing I can be sure of is that I will continue to explore.

- Click the mouse to save an artwork.
- Collectors who own this NFT have the right to print the work.

Artist: Aluan Wang (ileivoivm).
Made with p5js and glsl.

metadata.name: Mandelroid #122
metadata.description:
The Mandelbrot set is a mathematical object that is generated by a simple formula, and it exhibits some interesting visual patterns that are reminiscent of those found in nature, such as the self-similarity of branching structures, the repetition of small-scale patterns on larger scales, and the presence of chaotic behavior.

The beauty of Polaroid film lies in its ability to capture and preserve a moment in space and time in a unique and tangible way.

This work combines two things that are incongruent with each other and brings them together to create a digital memory that serves as a reminder that complexity can be found even in the simplest things, that art is intrinsic to nature itself.

• press '1' to scale the photo to 1024x1024 pixels (the default output)
• press '2' to scale the photo to 2048x2048 pixels (Warning: can be slow!)
• press '3' to scale the photo to 4096x4096 pixels (Warning: can be very slow!)
• press 'd' to save the Mandelbrot Set
• press 's' to save the Polaroid film

Done with p5.js
Simone "OuterSilent" Ferrari | @outertales | December 2022
